# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] A presidential election was held in Pennsylvania on January 7, 1789, as part of the 1788–89 United States presidential election.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] Voters chose 10 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania unanimously voted for nonpartisan candidate and commander-in-chief of the Continental Army, George Washington.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-pennsylvania] The total vote is composed of 6,718 for Federalist electors, known as the Lancaster Ticket, and 912 for Anti-Federalist electors, known as the Harrisburg Ticket, all of whom were supportive of Washington.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] An election to the United States House of Representatives was held in Pennsylvania on November 26, 1788, for the 1st Congress.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature ratified the Constitution on December 12, 1787, by a vote of 46–23.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of senators and representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature scheduled the election for November 26, 1788, and provided for it to be held on an at-large basis.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This was an attempt by the Federalist-dominated legislature to prevent anti-Federalist Representatives from being elected in frontier districts.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Both parties submitted tickets with 8 candidates each.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The large German population in Pennsylvania tended to vote for German candidates, giving the Anti-Federalist Muhlenberg and Hiester enough votes to gain seats.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The **1788 United States Senate election in Pennsylvania**, held on September 30, 1788, was the first United States Senate election held in Pennsylvania.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States Senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class I seat, while Federalist and American Founding Father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class III seat.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] Upon the expiration of Senator Maclay's term in 1791, the State House of Representatives would not be able to elect a new United States senator due to a dispute regarding the rules and procedures of the election.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1788-united-states-senate-elections-in-pennsylvania] The seat was finally filled in a 1793 election.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The first federal elections were held in the United States following the ratification of the United States Constitution in 1788.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] In the elections, George Washington was elected as the first president and the members of the 1st United States Congress were selected.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Opposing them was the Anti-Administration faction, which sought a smaller role for the federal government.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] In these elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Meanwhile, General George Washington was elected as the country's first president, while John Adams, who finished with the second largest number of electoral votes, was elected as the first vice president.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The presidential election of 1788–1789 was the first election of a federal head of state or head of government in United States history.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The Congress of the Confederation had elected a president, but this position was one of legislative presiding officer and was not equivalent to the presidency that was established by the United States Constitution.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Constitution, the president was chosen by the Electoral College, which consisted of electors selected by each state.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Prior to the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, each elector cast two votes; the individual who received the most electoral votes would become president, while the individual who received the second-most electoral votes would become vice president.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] If no individual received votes from a majority of the electors, or if two individuals tied for the most votes, then the House of Representatives would select the president in a contingent election.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Under the Constitution, each state determines its own method of choosing presidential electors; in the 1788–1789 presidential election, many electors were appointed by state legislators, while others were chosen through elections.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] In the states that did hold elections, suffrage was generally restricted to white men who owned property.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] No party made a nomination for the presidency in the 1788–1789 presidential election, but several individuals vied for electoral votes.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] After his service in the American Revolutionary War, General George Washington was the first choice of many for president, but Washington was somewhat reluctant to re-enter public service.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The American public at large, however, wanted Washington to be the nation's first president.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The first U.S. presidential campaign was, to some degree, what today would be called a grassroots effort to convince Washington to accept the office.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Alexander Hamilton was one of the most dedicated in his efforts to get Washington to accept the presidency, as he foresaw himself receiving a powerful position in the administration.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Less certain was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained little definitive job description in the constitution.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The only official role of the vice president was as the President of the United States Senate, a duty unrelated to the executive branch.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Because Washington was from Virginia, Washington (who remained neutral on the candidates) assumed that a vice president would be chosen from Massachusetts to provide sectional balance between the Northern states and the Southern states.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] In an August 1788 letter, Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams, John Hancock, John Jay, James Madison, and John Rutledge to be contenders for the vice presidency.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Fearing an electoral college tie that could end with Adams winning the presidency, Alexander Hamilton arranged for several electors to vote for other candidates, including John Jay, who finished with the third most electoral votes.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] On April 6, 1789, the House and Senate, meeting in joint session, counted the electoral votes and certified that Washington had received electoral votes from each of the 69 electors that had cast votes, and thus had been elected president.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] They also certified that Adams, with 34 electoral votes, had been elected as vice president.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The other 35 electoral votes were divided among: John Jay (9), Robert H.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Harrison (6), John Rutledge (6), John Hancock (4), George Clinton (3), Samuel Huntington (2), John Milton (2), James Armstrong (1), Benjamin Lincoln (1), and Edward Telfair (1).
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Only ten of the thirteen states cast electoral votes; North Carolina and Rhode Island did not participate as they had not yet ratified the Constitution, while the New York legislature failed to appoint its allotted electors in time.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] In 1788 and 1789, there were no political parties, but the major political split was between federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and anti-federalists who favored either completely rejecting the Constitution or only ratifying the document after making major changes to it.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] For example, in the election to represent Virginia's 5th congressional district, James Madison, a federalist who had played a major role in designing and ratifying the Constitution, defeated James Monroe, an anti-federalist who favored major changes to the Constitution.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] In many elections, local issues and the personal popularity of the candidates played a more important role than positions on the Constitution and other national issues.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Retrospectively, political scientists and historians have divided the 1st Congress into members of the Pro-Administration and Anti-Administration factions.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction would generally support the centralizing economic policies of the Washington administration and Secretary of State Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The Anti-Administration faction generally opposed those policies, instead favoring states' rights and a weaker federal government.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] The Pro-Administration faction overlapped heavily with both the federalists who favored the ratification of the Constitution and the later Federalist Party, while the Anti-Administration faction overlapped with the anti-federalists and the later Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Using this divide as a lens through which to view the elections, the Pro-Administration faction won majorities in both houses of Congress.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1789-united-states-elections] Factional alignment would be fluid for much of the Washington administration.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] The **1790 Connecticut gubernatorial election** was held on April 8, 1790, in order to elect the Governor of Connecticut.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Federalist Governor of Connecticut Samuel Huntington won re-election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 8, 1790, Federalist nominee Samuel Huntington easily won re-election as he ran unopposed.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-connecticut-gubernatorial-election] Huntington was sworn in for his fifth term on May 11, 1790.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] The **1790 Connecticut lieutenant gubernatorial election** was held on April 12, 1790, in order to elect the lieutenant governor of Connecticut.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Federalist lieutenant governor Oliver Wolcott was re-elected unopposed by the Connecticut legislature.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] On election day, April 12, 1790, incumbent Federalist lieutenant governor Oliver Wolcott was re-elected unopposed by the Connecticut legislature.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-connecticut-lieutenant-gubernatorial-election] Wolcott was sworn in for his fifth term on May 13, 1790.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] The **1790 Pennsylvania gubernatorial election** was the first gubernatorial election after the establishment of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania as a U.S. state.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] Thomas Mifflin, the incumbent President of the Supreme Executive Council of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania was elected as the first Governor of Pennsylvania.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] He defeated Federalist candidate Arthur St.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election] Clair, former Revolutionary War general and President of the Continental Congress, by a wide margin.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1790-pennsylvania-gubernatorial-election/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-connecticut] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
